  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'What does GABA do for the brain?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'GABA (gamma-aminobutyric acid) is the brain\'s primary inhibitory neurotransmitter. It reduces neuronal excitability by binding to GABA receptors on nerve cells, decreasing the firing rate of neurons. This inhibitory action produces calming effects: reduced anxiety, lower stress response, muscle relaxation, and promotion of sleep. GABA is the natural counterbalance to glutamate, the brain\'s primary excitatory neurotransmitter. When GABA levels are low relative to glutamate, the brain becomes overexcited — manifesting as anxiety, racing thoughts, insomnia, and muscle tension. Prescription medications like benzodiazepines and barbiturates work by enhancing GABA receptor activity.' } },
  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'Does oral GABA cross the blood-brain barrier?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'This is the central debate in GABA supplementation science. Traditional pharmacology holds that GABA poorly crosses the blood-brain barrier (BBB). However, emerging research challenges this assumption. A 2015 study using PET scanning found that oral GABA did reach the brain in measurable quantities. PharmaGABA (a naturally fermented form) has shown clinical benefits in human trials despite the BBB question — reducing stress markers, improving sleep quality, and increasing alpha brain wave activity within 60 minutes. GABA may also work through the gut-brain axis via vagal nerve signaling and through peripheral GABA receptors. The clinical evidence shows that oral GABA supplements produce measurable effects, even if the exact mechanism is still debated.' } },
  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'What is the difference between GABA and PharmaGABA?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Standard GABA supplements use synthetic gamma-aminobutyric acid produced through chemical synthesis. PharmaGABA is a naturally produced form created through the fermentation of Lactobacillus hilgardii (a beneficial bacteria) — the same process used to make traditional Asian fermented foods like kimchi and tempeh. Clinical studies specifically using PharmaGABA have shown: increased alpha brain wave activity (associated with calm alertness) within 60 minutes, reduced stress biomarkers (salivary IgA, cortisol), and improved sleep quality. PharmaGABA may have superior bioavailability compared to synthetic GABA, though both forms are considered safe. PharmaGABA is more expensive but has more direct clinical evidence.' } },
