    <h2 id="why-gaba">How GABA Calms the Nervous System</h2>

    <p>GABA (gamma-aminobutyric acid) is the brain's primary inhibitory neurotransmitter — it is the molecular "off switch" that reduces neuronal firing rate, calms the central nervous system, and counterbalances the excitatory effects of glutamate. When GABA binds to its receptors on neurons, it opens chloride ion channels that make the neuron less likely to fire, producing a net calming effect throughout the brain. This mechanism underlies the effects of some of the most powerful anti-anxiety and sleep medications ever developed: benzodiazepines (Xanax, Valium), barbiturates, and the newer Z-drugs (Ambien) all work by enhancing GABA receptor activity.</p>

    <div class="key-stat">
      <span class="key-stat-num">40%</span>
      <p class="key-stat-txt">of all brain synapses use GABA as their neurotransmitter. When GABA activity is low, the brain becomes overexcited — producing <strong>anxiety, racing thoughts, insomnia, muscle tension, and irritability</strong>. Chronic stress depletes GABA levels, creating a vicious cycle: stress reduces GABA, low GABA increases stress sensitivity, and the cycle perpetuates.</p>
    </div>

