      <div class="info-card"><div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="moon" size={22} /></div><strong>Sleep Promotion</strong><p>GABA reduces the neuronal firing rate that keeps you awake. Clinical studies show GABA supplementation reduces sleep onset latency (time to fall asleep) and increases total sleep time. It addresses the "can't turn off my brain" insomnia pattern.</p></div>
      <div class="info-card"><div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="heart" size={22} /></div><strong>Stress Response</strong><p>GABA modulates the HPA axis (hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal axis) that controls cortisol release. PharmaGABA has been shown to reduce salivary cortisol and salivary IgA (stress immunoglobulin) under experimental stress conditions.</p></div>
      <div class="info-card"><div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="fitness" size={22} /></div><strong>Muscle Relaxation</strong><p>GABA receptors exist on motor neurons and in muscle tissue. GABA activity reduces muscle tension and spasticity. The muscle-relaxant effects of benzodiazepines are mediated entirely through GABA receptor enhancement. Supplemental GABA provides milder but similar muscle relaxation.</p></div>
    </div>

