    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About GABA Gummies</h2>
    <details class="fq"><summary>What does GABA do for the brain?</summary><p>GABA is the primary inhibitory neurotransmitter — it reduces neuronal excitability, producing calm. It counterbalances excitatory glutamate. Low GABA causes anxiety, racing thoughts, insomnia, and muscle tension. Prescription anti-anxiety drugs work by enhancing GABA activity.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Does oral GABA cross the blood-brain barrier?</summary><p>Debated in pharmacology. Emerging evidence (including PET scans) suggests some oral GABA reaches the brain. PharmaGABA clinical studies show measurable brain effects (260% alpha wave increase). GABA may also work via gut-brain axis and peripheral receptors.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>What is PharmaGABA vs regular GABA?</summary><p>PharmaGABA is naturally fermented by Lactobacillus hilgardii. It has more direct clinical evidence (alpha waves, cortisol reduction). Standard GABA is synthetically produced. PharmaGABA may have superior bioavailability. Both are safe.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>How much GABA for sleep?</summary><p>PharmaGABA: 100-200mg. Synthetic GABA: 200-500mg. Take 30-60 minutes before bed. Start low and increase gradually. GABA works synergistically with magnesium, L-theanine, and melatonin for better results than increasing dose alone.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Can I take GABA with melatonin?</summary><p>Yes. They work through different mechanisms: melatonin regulates sleep timing (circadian rhythm), GABA calms the nervous system (reduces racing thoughts). Together they address both falling asleep and staying calm. Start with low doses of each.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Are GABA gummies safe?</summary><p>Safe for most healthy adults at 100-750mg. Mild tingling possible at higher doses. Do NOT combine with benzodiazepines, barbiturates, or sedative medications. Consult physician if you have depression. Avoid during pregnancy/breastfeeding.</p></details>

